<section class="app-page-shell cookie-page-shell">
    <section class="app-page-header cookie-page-hero">
        <div class="cookie-page-copy">
            <p class="cookie-page-eyebrow">Cookie Policy</p>
            <h1>How HelloUniversity uses cookies and similar browser-side technologies.</h1>
            <p class="cookie-page-lead">
                This notice explains how the main HelloUniversity platform may use session cookies, local storage, analytics, and similar technologies to keep the site working, support account access, remember preferences, and understand service performance.
            </p>

            <div class="cookie-page-meta">
                <span class="cookie-page-chip">Last updated: June 9, 2026</span>
                <span class="cookie-page-chip">Operated by 4HProjects</span>
            </div>
        </div>

        <aside class="cookie-page-note">
            <p class="cookie-page-note-label">At a glance</p>
            <h2>What this page covers</h2>
            <ul class="cookie-page-note-list">
                <li>Session cookies and similar technologies used for authentication and security</li>
                <li>Preference storage used to keep browser-side interface choices</li>
                <li>Analytics or third-party technologies that may appear on certain public pages</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="cookie-page-note-meta">
                For broader handling of personal information, see the <a href="/privacy-policy">Privacy Policy</a>.
            </p>
        </aside>
    </section>

    <section class="cookie-page-grid">
        <article class="app-panel cookie-page-panel">
            <div class="cookie-page-section-heading">
                <p class="cookie-page-section-eyebrow">Scope</p>
                <h2>What cookies and similar technologies are</h2>
            </div>
            <p>
                Cookies are small text files that a site or service can place in a browser. HelloUniversity may also use similar browser-side technologies such as session identifiers, local storage, or third-party service tags when they are needed for platform operation or enabled on a page.
            </p>
            <p>
                This page is a platform-level operational notice for the main HelloUniversity site. Actual browser behavior can vary depending on whether a user is signed in, which page is visited, and whether a page loads embedded or third-party services.
            </p>
        </article>

        <aside class="app-panel app-panel-muted cookie-page-panel cookie-page-side-panel">
            <p class="cookie-page-section-eyebrow">Current Product Context</p>
            <h2>What the main site uses today</h2>
            <ul class="cookie-page-list cookie-page-list-compact">
                <li>Session cookies for authenticated account access and security controls.</li>
                <li>Browser storage for interface preferences where a page supports them.</li>
                <li>Google Analytics 4 on all pages for traffic and usage measurement.</li>
                <li>Google AdSense on pages where ads are enabled.</li>
                <li>Google reCAPTCHA v3 on the signup page for bot protection.</li>
                <li>Google Fonts loaded on all pages for typography.</li>
            </ul>
        </aside>
    </section>

    <section class="cookie-page-section">
        <div class="cookie-page-section-heading">
            <p class="cookie-page-section-eyebrow">Categories</p>
            <h2>How these technologies may be used</h2>
            <p>The exact set can change as features are added, removed, or reconfigured.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="cookie-page-card-grid">
            <article class="app-panel cookie-page-card">
                <span class="material-icons cookie-page-card-icon" aria-hidden="true">verified_user</span>
                <h3>Essential session and security cookies</h3>
                <p>These help keep users signed in, maintain authenticated sessions, apply security settings, and support reliable platform access.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="app-panel cookie-page-card">
                <span class="material-icons cookie-page-card-icon" aria-hidden="true">tune</span>
                <h3>Preference storage</h3>
                <p>Some pages may store interface choices such as theme or similar user preferences so the site can remember them between visits.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="app-panel cookie-page-card">
                <span class="material-icons cookie-page-card-icon" aria-hidden="true">monitoring</span>
                <h3>Analytics and diagnostics</h3>
                <p>Google Analytics 4 is used to understand site reliability, traffic patterns, feature usage, and service improvement opportunities. It is present on all pages, including authenticated areas.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="app-panel cookie-page-card">
                <span class="material-icons cookie-page-card-icon" aria-hidden="true">extension</span>
                <h3>Third-party service cookies</h3>
                <p>Some pages load external services that may set their own cookies or transmit browser data to their servers. The following third-party services are currently in use:</p>
                <ul class="cookie-page-list cookie-page-list-compact" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
                    <li><strong>Google Analytics 4</strong> — present on all pages, including authenticated areas, to measure traffic and feature usage. See <a href="https://support.google.com/analytics/answer/6004245" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google Analytics data privacy</a>.</li>
                    <li><strong>Google AdSense</strong> — advertising scripts present on pages where ads are enabled. See <a href="https://policies.google.com/technologies/ads" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google advertising privacy</a>.</li>
                    <li><strong>Google reCAPTCHA v3</strong> — loaded on the signup page to detect automated activity. No persistent cookie is set, but a token and IP address are sent to Google for verification. See <a href="https://policies.google.com/privacy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google's Privacy Policy</a>.</li>
                    <li><strong>Google Fonts</strong> — font files loaded from <code>fonts.googleapis.com</code> on all pages. Google may log request metadata such as IP address and browser type.</li>
                </ul>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="cookie-page-grid">
        <article class="app-panel cookie-page-panel">
            <div class="cookie-page-section-heading">
                <p class="cookie-page-section-eyebrow">Duration</p>
                <h2>Session and persistent storage</h2>
            </div>
            <ul class="cookie-page-list">
                <li><strong>Session cookies</strong> may expire when the browser is closed or when the active session times out.</li>
                <li><strong>Persistent cookies or browser storage</strong> can remain for a longer period so the platform or a third-party service can remember settings, measure visits, or keep service state across sessions.</li>
                <li>Retention can vary depending on the feature, provider, browser configuration, and whether a user clears stored site data manually.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>

        <aside class="app-panel cookie-page-panel cookie-page-manage-panel">
            <p class="cookie-page-section-eyebrow">Control</p>
            <h2>How users can manage cookies</h2>
            <ul class="cookie-page-list cookie-page-list-compact">
                <li>Use browser settings to block, delete, or limit cookies and site data.</li>
                <li>Sign out of authenticated sessions when using shared devices.</li>
                <li>Use browser privacy controls or extensions to manage third-party technologies.</li>
                <li>Expect some login, preference, search, or embedded features to work less reliably if browser storage is disabled.</li>
            </ul>
        </aside>
    </section>

    <section class="cookie-page-grid">
        <article class="app-panel cookie-page-panel">
            <div class="cookie-page-section-heading">
                <p class="cookie-page-section-eyebrow">Third-Party Services</p>
                <h2>Page-level differences can happen</h2>
            </div>
            <p>
                Not every HelloUniversity page uses the same browser-side technologies. Some public pages can load external services such as programmable search or advertising scripts, while core authenticated workflows rely more directly on session management and security-related cookies.
            </p>
            <p>
                When a third-party service is loaded, that provider may process browser data under its own terms or privacy notice. Users should review those provider notices where relevant.
            </p>
        </article>

